	</aside>
	<!--interrupt--></div>
<p>Looming in the background is a push from lawmakers to update varying parts of the music licensing system.</p> <p>Reps. Jerry Nadler (D-N.Y.), Doug Collins (R-Ga.) and John Conyers (D-Mich.) are all likely to reintroduce reform bills this year. House Judiciary Committee Chairman Bob Goodlatte (R-Va.), whose panel launched a comprehensive copyright law review during the last session of Congress, has said the effort will continue.</p> <p>As Washington digs deeper into the topic, music industry groups in D.C. are pleading with well-known artists and songwriters <a href="http://www.politico.com/story/2014/12/digital-music-copyright-war-113779.html" target="_blank">to get more involved</a> in the debate and use their star power to draw attention to disparities in the system. Taylor Swift&rsquo;s recent skirmish with Spotify over what that platform pays artists &mdash; a spat that generated national headlines &mdash; helped ignite new debate over the value of music.</p> <p>&ldquo;We are living in a musical landscape that&rsquo;s changing so quickly, especially with technology,&rdquo; said Kimberly Perry, lead singer of Grammy-nominated The Band Perry, who visited the Capitol for a concert and meetings with lawmakers last month. &ldquo;To be completely honest, I&rsquo;m interested in learning more about our business and asking questions that I don&rsquo;t necessarily know the answers to.&rdquo;</p>

